  <h1 id="title">Eileen Chang (Zhang Ailing)</h1>
  <h2>Life as tragic as her stories</h2>
  <div id="img-div">
    <img id="image" src="https://www.silkgauzeaudio.com/wp-content/uploads/Eileen-Chang-resized.jpg" alt="Eileen Chang">
    <p id="caption">Elegant Eileen Chang being photographed</p>
    <hr>
    <section id="tribute-info">
      <h2 id="bio">Her biography (1920-1995)</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Born into an aristocratic family in Shanghai as Zhang Ailing with a conservative opium addict as her father and a sophisticated half-English educated woman as her mother</li>
        <li>Their unhappy marriage ended in divorce and Chang ran away from her abusive father</li>
        <li>Went to study literature at the University of Hong Kong</li>
        <li>The Japanese attack in 1941 forced her to return to occupied Shanghai</li>
        <li>Published the stories and essays (collected in two volumes, <i>Romances</i>, 1944, and <i>Written on Water</i>, 1945) that made her a literary star</li>
        <li>Married Hu Lancheng, a Japanese sympathizer whose cheating tendecies led to their divorce three years later</li>
        <li>Moved to Hong Kong in 1952 due to the rise of Communist influence</li>
        <li>Immigrated to the United States three years later</li>
        <li>Remarried an American named Ferdinand Reyher who died in 1967) and held various posts as writer-in-residence</li>
        <li>Obtained more permanent position as a researcher at Berkeley</li>
        <li>Two novels which served as anti-Communist propaganda, <i>The Rice Sprout Song</i> and <i>Naked Earth</i>, were followed by a third, <i>The Rouge of the North</i> (1967), which expanded on her celebrated early novella,<i>The Golden Cangue</i></li>
        <li>Continued writing essays and stories in Chinese, scripts for Hong Kong films</li>
        <li>Began work on an English translation work of the famous Qing novel, <i>The Sing-Song Girls of Shanghai</i></li>
        <li>Became more reclusive as she grew older in spite of the tremendous revival on interest in her work in the 1970s</li>
        <li>Found dead in her Los Angeles apartment in September 1995</li>
      </ul>
      <p>To understand her fatalistic POV and cry to melodramatic Chinese literature, you can purchase her books <a id="tribute-link" href="https://www.bookdepository.com/search?searchTerm=eileen+chang&search=Find+book" target="_blank">here</a>! :')
        </p>
    </section>
  </div>
